# Circuit Notes — Pin Mapping

## Arduino UNO/Nano Pin Assignments

| Arduino Pin | Connected To | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| D2 | IR Sensor 1 (OUT) | Interrupt pin, falling-edge trigger |
| D3 | IR Sensor 2 (OUT) | Interrupt pin, falling-edge trigger |
| D5 | L298N IN1 | Motor direction control |
| D6 | L298N IN2 | Motor direction control |
| D8 | Buzzer (+) | Active buzzer, direct drive |
| D9 | LED (+) via 220Ω resistor | Over-speed visual indicator |
| D10 | L298N ENA | PWM motor speed control |
| 5V | IR Sensor VCC (both) | Shared 5V rail |
| GND | Common ground | Shared across Arduino, L298N, sensors, buzzer |

## L298N Motor Driver

| L298N Pin | Connected To |
|---|---|
| IN1 | Arduino D5 |
| IN2 | Arduino D6 |
| ENA | Arduino D10 (PWM) |
| OUT1 | DC Motor terminal 1 |
| OUT2 | DC Motor terminal 2 |
| +12V | External battery positive |
| GND | External battery negative + Arduino GND |

## Notes
- The two IR sensors should be mounted at a **fixed, known distance** apart (default in code: 0.20 m) along the path the object/wheel travels.
- Use a common ground between the Arduino and the L298N module's external power supply — this is critical, otherwise PWM signals will not behave correctly.
- If using a 9V battery for the motor, ensure the L298N's onboard 5V regulator jumper is set correctly (remove it if supplying 5V separately to the Arduino).
 
